Here's an example program in JavaScript that finds the common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures:
```
function findCommonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  let commonElements = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    if (arr2.includes(arr1[i])) {
      commonElements.push(arr1[i]);
    }
  }

  return commonElements;
}
```
This program uses the `includes()` method to check if each element in `arr1` is present in `arr2`. If an element is found in `arr2`, it is added to the `commonElements` array.

Here's an example usage of the function:
```
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const arr2 = [4, 5, 6, 7, 8];

const commonElements = findCommonElements(arr1, arr2);
console.log(commonElements); // Output: [4, 5]
```
